Below is one systematic way to see how the target picture is made from the dictionary blocks (with **no** extra rotations).  I will first describe what is in the target image (how many blocks, how they are layered and arranged), then specify exactly which dictionary‐blocks (by index) are used, and finally give a step‐by‐step assembly order.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
1)  ANALYSIS OF THE MAIN TARGET IMAGE
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
•  The scene contains two separate “mini‐structures.”

•  LEFT STRUCTURE  
   –  Total of 6 blocks in 2 vertical levels.  
   –  Base‐Level (5 blocks):  
      1. One tall orange cylinder in the center.  
      2. Two small blue rectangular blocks flanking the cylinder (one on each side).  
      3. Two orange wedges (one on the left, one on the right) resting against the cylinder.  
   –  Top‐Level (1 block):  
      1. A single orange wedge perched on top of the cylinder as a “roof.”  

•  RIGHT STRUCTURE  
   –  Total of 5 blocks, effectively in two layers.  
   –  Base‐Level (3 blocks side‐by‐side):  
      1. A tall blue rectangular pillar on the far left.  
      2. A red arch block in the center (arch opening faces front‐to‐back).  
      3. A green cube on the right.  
   –  Second‐Level (2 blocks):  
      1. A long yellow rectangular block bridging across the tops of the blue pillar and green cube.  
      2. An orange wedge block set on top as the “roof.”  

Hence the entire target uses 11 total blocks: 6 on the left, 5 on the right.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
2)  SELECTING THE CORRECT DICTIONARY BLOCKS
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Below are the dictionary indices (in parentheses) that match each visible piece **without** re‐orienting them beyond the way they appear in the dictionary images.

● LEFT STRUCTURE
1) Cylinder (tall orange) → index 12  
2) Blue rectangles (two identical pieces) → index 6 (used twice)  
3) Orange wedges around base → indices 13 and 16  
4) Orange wedge on top → index 15  

● RIGHT STRUCTURE
1) Tall blue pillar (vertical rectangle) → index 6 (used again here)  
2) Red arch (opening front‐to‐back) → index 2  
3) Green cube → index 5  
4) Yellow rectangular block (horizontal “beam”) → index 8  
5) Orange wedge “roof” → index 14  

In summary, the blocks needed (with exact orientations as shown) are:  
• #2 (red arch),  
• #5 (green cube),  
• #6 (blue rectangular) → used three times total,  
• #8 (yellow rectangular beam),  
• #12 (orange cylinder),  
• #13 / #15 / #16 (three different orange wedge orientations),  
• #14 (fourth orange wedge orientation).

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
3)  STEP‐BY‐STEP ASSEMBLY ORDER
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Below is one possible order, listing each “move block with index …” in sequence:

{
  Step1:  Move block with index 12   // place tall orange cylinder (left structure)
  Step2:  Move block with index 6    // first small blue rectangle at cylinder’s side
  Step3:  Move block with index 6    // second small blue rectangle at other side
  Step4:  Move block with index 13   // first orange wedge against cylinder base
  Step5:  Move block with index 16   // second orange wedge against cylinder base
  Step6:  Move block with index 15   // orange wedge on top of cylinder (roof)

  Step7:  Move block with index 6    // tall blue pillar (right structure)
  Step8:  Move block with index 2    // red arch in center
  Step9:  Move block with index 5    // green cube on right
  Step10: Move block with index 8    // yellow rectangular beam across top
  Step11: Move block with index 14   // orange wedge on top as final roof
}

That completes the target scene exactly as shown, using only the provided orientations of the dictionary blocks.
